WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.389 --> 00:00:03.056
(gentle music)

2
00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:11.122
<v David>Okay, Dr. Conner, take it away.</v>

3
00:00:11.122 --> 00:00:11.955
Pulmonary III.
<v ->Thank you, David.</v>

4
00:00:11.955 --> 00:00:14.640
Let's jump in. Pulmonary infections.

5
00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:18.720
So in 2019, the Infectious Disease Society of America,

6
00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.540
American Thoracic Society, updated their guidelines

7
00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:22.920
for the diagnosis and treatments

8
00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:24.210
of community-acquired pneumonia,

9
00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:27.000
so a few things have changed since then.

10
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:28.650
Interestingly, pneumonias are still the eighth

11
00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:30.690
leading cause of death in the United States.

12
00:00:30.690 --> 00:00:33.480
The mortality rate disproportionately affects

13
00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:37.200
the extremes of ages, as you might expect.

14
00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.470
How do bacteria get into the lungs and set up a problem?

15
00:00:40.470 --> 00:00:42.120
Well, there's three areas.

16
00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:43.893
You can inhale the bacteria.

17
00:00:45.270 --> 00:00:48.960
Interestingly, we'll talk about this in a moment.

18
00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:50.160
There's a specific bacteria

19
00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:52.230
that likes to live in the air ducts,

20
00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:55.890
that if you have been in a hotel or a cruise ship

21
00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.020
and within the next two weeks develop pneumonia,

22
00:00:58.020 --> 00:01:00.330
you should be tested for what?

23
00:01:00.330 --> 00:01:01.620
Legionella, right.

24
00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:03.543
Legionella lives up in the air ducts.

25
00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:07.413
Named after a famous convention,

26
00:01:08.292 --> 00:01:11.880
Legionnaires Convention in Philadelphia, I believe in 1976,

27
00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:14.130
there's a minor version of the illness

28
00:01:14.130 --> 00:01:15.360
called Pontiac Fever,

29
00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:18.390
Pontiac from North of Detroit where I live.

30
00:01:18.390 --> 00:01:20.070
And that tends to be more the fever

31
00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:22.740
without the respiratory problem, but also due to Legionella.

32
00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:26.940
Anyway, you can breathe the bacteria in,

33
00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:28.350
you can aspirate it,

34
00:01:28.350 --> 00:01:31.380
or it can spread via the hematogenous route.

35
00:01:31.380 --> 00:01:34.620
For example, if you had pyelonephritis, for example,

36
00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:37.383
and it moved up to the lungs via the bloodstream.

37
00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:40.680
The etiology here, this one's easy,

38
00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:44.700
common pathogen Strep pneumo, Myco, Chlamydia, H. flu.

39
00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:48.060
What's more interesting are the less common pathogens

40
00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:49.710
and even more interesting than that

41
00:01:49.710 --> 00:01:51.660
are the modifying factors.

42
00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:53.790
So this is what I want you to pay attention to.

43
00:01:53.790 --> 00:01:55.410
We all know Strep pneumo,

44
00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:58.230
but what changes our thinking

45
00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:01.470
from the ordinary to the atypical?

46
00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:02.880
And here's what they are.

47
00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:05.520
So young patients age four months to four years,

48
00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.430
RSV is you're more likely agent it.

49
00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:11.823
Age 5 to 18, it's Mycoplasma pneumoniae.

50
00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:16.740
Now, these are also very important modifying factors.

51
00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:17.910
Look at these.

52
00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:19.350
If a patient's alcoholic,

53
00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:22.020
you wanna think anaerobes and Klebsiella.

54
00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:24.360
Aspiration, anaerobes.

55
00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:28.863
Bioterrorism, those are the agents that you might consider.

56
00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:32.310
Thankfully, we haven't seen bioterrorism in a minute,

57
00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:34.740
but could still happen.

58
00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:38.520
COPD patients tend to be infected with H. flu or M. cat.

59
00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:41.130
Exposure to farm animals or droppings,

60
00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:44.790
Histo, Blasto, and Cocci are your fungal organisms.

61
00:02:44.790 --> 00:02:46.860
And we will discuss those later this afternoon

62
00:02:46.860 --> 00:02:50.520
'cause those wills show up on the boards, I guarantee.

63
00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:52.590
Hotel or cruise ship travel, within the past two weeks,

64
00:02:52.590 --> 00:02:54.330
as we just mentioned, Legionella.

65
00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:57.570
Post influenza, think Staph aureus.

66
00:02:57.570 --> 00:03:00.090
These are very important to remember for the boards,

67
00:03:00.090 --> 00:03:03.420
as well as clinical practice, as are these.

68
00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:06.690
Increased risk for drug-resistant Strep pneumo,

69
00:03:06.690 --> 00:03:09.120
age greater than 65.

70
00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:13.050
Any broad spectrum antibiotics within the last three months.

71
00:03:13.050 --> 00:03:15.510
The boards like to ask the question,

72
00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:18.960
well, he was at the dentist, you know, a month or two ago

73
00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:22.200
and was put on clindamycin or whatnot,

74
00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:24.660
amoxicillin for his dental infection,

75
00:03:24.660 --> 00:03:25.560
blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

76
00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:27.750
Now what should you do to treat his pneumonia?

77
00:03:27.750 --> 00:03:29.610
Well, he's up to a high risk group now

78
00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:31.770
because the dentist gave him a broad spectrum antibiotic

79
00:03:31.770 --> 00:03:33.020
in the last three months.

80
00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:36.870
Alcohol abuse, immunosuppressive illnesses,

81
00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:39.180
multiple medical comorbidities,

82
00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:41.070
obviously including diabetes.

83
00:03:41.070 --> 00:03:43.500
Exposure to children in a daycare center

84
00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:46.110
increases your risk for drug resistant strep.

85
00:03:46.110 --> 00:03:47.550
Very interesting.

86
00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:48.383
And like I said,

87
00:03:48.383 --> 00:03:51.570
they love to throw these questions at you on the boards.

88
00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:54.720
Increased risk for MRSA. I've had MRSA in the past.

89
00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:57.450
A lot of patients tend to be carriers as you know.

90
00:03:57.450 --> 00:04:00.270
Hospitalization and antibiotics in the last 90 days,

91
00:04:00.270 --> 00:04:03.810
or locally validated factors that might include MRSA

92
00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:05.820
and immunocompromised patients.

93
00:04:05.820 --> 00:04:07.120
Keep all of those in mind.

94
00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:10.380
Your presentation of pneumonia, typical presentation,

95
00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:13.410
you all know how to diagnose pneumonia, that's easy.

96
00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:15.990
What's more interesting is the atypical presentations,

97
00:04:15.990 --> 00:04:17.490
which can be subacute.

98
00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:19.500
In elderly, they can come across

99
00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.810
as maybe functional decline.

100
00:04:21.810 --> 00:04:24.870
The physical exam symptoms might be more subtle.

101
00:04:24.870 --> 00:04:26.880
They might only include one respiratory symptom,

102
00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:28.170
but they may have a bunch of other

103
00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:30.150
extra pulmonary symptoms as well.

104
00:04:30.150 --> 00:04:33.630
So keep that in mind with your atypical pneumonias.

105
00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:37.200
Also, social travel, like I'll give you a test question

106
00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:38.490
this afternoon about a patient

107
00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:40.800
who was visiting a certain part of the country

108
00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:42.850
and came back with an atypical pneumonia.

109
00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:46.200
Okay, let's get started with a question.

110
00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:47.413
Now, here's our case.

111
00:04:47.413 --> 00:04:50.613
A 55-year-old male presents, wait a minute,

112
00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:54.750
didn't I say that I don't use sex

113
00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:59.220
in the stem of my question except unless what?

114
00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:02.070
Right, so a 55-year-old male

115
00:05:02.070 --> 00:05:04.320
presents with a four-day history of productive cough, fever,

116
00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:07.890
some dull right flank pain, and mild dyspnea.

117
00:05:07.890 --> 00:05:09.330
Past medical history is significant

118
00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:11.250
for diabetes and hypertension.

119
00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:12.720
His exam is unremarkable

120
00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:15.750
besides a temperature of 101 degrees Fahrenheit,

121
00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:17.910
respirations of 22,

122
00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:19.110
pulse of 110,

123
00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:20.973
BP 100/70.

124
00:05:22.170 --> 00:05:23.550
There is dullness to percussion

125
00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:25.290
and some crackles in the left base.

126
00:05:25.290 --> 00:05:27.990
A chest x-ray shows a left lower lobe infiltrate.

127
00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:30.210
We all know what's going on here.

128
00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:31.350
Treatment is initiated.

129
00:05:31.350 --> 00:05:32.520
Which one of the following is true

130
00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:35.370
concerning further diagnostic studies in this case?

131
00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:38.910
A, a chest CT is recommended.

132
00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:42.450
B, a chest x-ray should be repeated in one to two weeks.

133
00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:44.880
C, no further diagnostic studies are recommended

134
00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:46.440
if symptoms resolve.

135
00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:49.233
Or D, ultrasound of chest and abdomen is recommended.

136
00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:52.050
Dr. Holt mentioned this to you earlier

137
00:05:52.050 --> 00:05:53.370
how the boards love to do this to you.

138
00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:54.840
They really ask you two questions in one.

139
00:05:54.840 --> 00:05:55.950
This one's pretty straightforward,

140
00:05:55.950 --> 00:05:59.580
but quite often, they'll present a case like this

141
00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:03.150
and you have to know what the diagnosis is.

142
00:06:03.150 --> 00:06:05.370
But the question may be, you know, what is the treatment

143
00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:06.630
or what's the next step?

144
00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:08.190
So they're really tricking you

145
00:06:08.190 --> 00:06:10.170
into answering two questions at once.

146
00:06:10.170 --> 00:06:11.820
The boards love to do that.

147
00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:15.570
In this case, we have a patient with pneumonia, right?

148
00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:16.770
Community-acquired pneumonia.

149
00:06:16.770 --> 00:06:19.863
So what should we do for follow up, if anything?

150
00:06:24.870 --> 00:06:27.390
Good, no further diagnostic studies recommended

151
00:06:27.390 --> 00:06:28.890
if the symptoms resolve.

152
00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:31.620
That's a change from the previous

153
00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:33.510
community-acquired pneumonia guidelines

154
00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:36.063
where they recommended a follow up chest x-ray.

155
00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:40.800
Really, you know, you don't need a chest x-ray

156
00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:41.820
to diagnose pneumonia.

157
00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:45.393
I can diagnose pneumonia with a history and my stethoscope,

158
00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:49.080
but you're gonna get the chest x-ray anyway

159
00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:51.510
because it may exclude some other causes,

160
00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:52.950
confirms your diagnosis,

161
00:06:52.950 --> 00:06:55.170
so it's just standard of care to do a chest x-ray

162
00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:57.900
when you suspect pneumonia.

163
00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:00.660
Your classic, you know, Strep pneumo

164
00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:03.063
is like this right middle lobe, you know,

165
00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:07.320
consolidated lobar lesion.

166
00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:10.500
Your atypicals may be more the fluffy interstitial

167
00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:12.270
bat wing type of appearance.

168
00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:14.340
Don't forget about false negatives with dehydrated

169
00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:15.930
or elderly patients.

170
00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:18.630
And again, repeat chest x-rays no longer recommended.

171
00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:19.770
Here's a couple radiographs.

172
00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:21.030
On the left, we see that typical

173
00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:22.680
right middle lobe infiltrate.

174
00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:24.720
Classic, classic pneumonia,

175
00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:27.030
And then on the right, an atypical,

176
00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:29.760
that kind of fluffy bat wing type of appearance

177
00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:30.753
that you may see.

178
00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:34.260
You can also use ultrasound

179
00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:36.090
to diagnose pneumonia if you have it available,

180
00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:38.580
and an experienced sonographer

181
00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:40.110
that can be used at the bedside

182
00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:43.170
and can be helpful to detect other disorders as well.

183
00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:45.750
And CT, especially if you're suspecting

184
00:07:45.750 --> 00:07:47.040
interstitial lung diseases,

185
00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:50.583
a tumor, sarcoid, or a malignancy.

186
00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:54.783
This is new too.

187
00:07:55.860 --> 00:08:00.360
Testing for specific pathogens with cultures

188
00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:03.390
and urine testing antigens is unnecessary now

189
00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:04.890
for most outpatients.

190
00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:07.623
If they're in the unit, completely different story.

191
00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:13.290
However, if they've been on antibiotics in the last 90 days

192
00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:14.123
or they're severe,

193
00:08:14.123 --> 00:08:16.230
you might wanna consider these other risk factors.

194
00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:19.470
These next two slides are for you to take home and study.

195
00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:23.280
This tells you every test

196
00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:26.403
that should be ordered in each individual case.

197
00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:32.520
Your normal patient you treated as an outpatient

198
00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:36.720
doesn't need blood cultures or sputum cultures, okay?

199
00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:39.570
But this tells you alcohol abuse, asplenia,

200
00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:41.910
cavitary infiltrate, chronic liver disease,

201
00:08:41.910 --> 00:08:44.100
outpatient treatment failure,

202
00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:48.000
ICU admit, leukopenia, pleural effusion, severe COPD,

203
00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.433
or recent travel, what tests you should order.

204
00:08:53.310 --> 00:08:54.723
Okay, next question.

205
00:08:55.710 --> 00:08:57.003
Same case.

206
00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:00.870
When deciding whether to treat your 55-year-old

207
00:09:00.870 --> 00:09:02.460
with pneumonia as an outpatient

208
00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.200
or to admit them to the hospital,

209
00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:06.180
in addition to clinical judgment,

210
00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:08.190
which one of the following tools

211
00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:10.140
or tests would be most helpful?

212
00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:12.900
Would it be A, the CURB-65?

213
00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.590
B, the Pneumonia Severity Index or PSI?

