00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:18.960
C, procalcitonin level?

215
00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:20.763
Or D, SMART-COP?

216
00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:30.150
One of these tools is most helpful if we're unsure

217
00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:33.630
whether we should admit the patient to the hospital or not.

218
00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:35.550
Sometimes with the boards, it's gonna be pretty obvious.

219
00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:36.383
You know, they're gonna have

220
00:09:36.383 --> 00:09:38.670
a hemodynamically unstable patient

221
00:09:38.670 --> 00:09:39.840
or there's something else going on

222
00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.960
where it's obvious they need to be in the hospital.

223
00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:44.910
In other cases, it may be more subtle

224
00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:47.360
and that's where questions like this can come in.

225
00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:55.290
Okay, so we have just a slight majority here.

226
00:09:55.290 --> 00:09:59.970
So learning opportunity, the PSI is the correct answer.

227
00:09:59.970 --> 00:10:02.640
It used to be the CURB-65.

228
00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:04.500
So those of you who answered that,

229
00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:07.050
you're still thinking it with the older guidelines.

230
00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.160
The PSI is the newer one.

231
00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:12.090
How about biomarkers?

232
00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:14.460
How many like procalcitonin levels

233
00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:15.810
in their pneumonia patient?

234
00:10:15.810 --> 00:10:17.340
I know they do them a lot in the hospital.

235
00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:19.530
They're considered out now.

236
00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:24.300
They're just not, they're not sensitive and specific enough.

