00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:47.640
So it is now recommended over the CURB-65

246
00:10:47.640 --> 00:10:49.263
severity of index score.

247
00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:52.350
So here's what it looks like.

248
00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:57.350
So over on the left, you stratify based on age.

249
00:10:58.020 --> 00:11:01.770
First off, over 55 years of age, our patient was 55,

250
00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:04.770
so he gets a yes for that.

251
00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:08.760
And then you move on to step number two, he's male.

252
00:11:08.760 --> 00:11:13.473
So you add his age in years, so 55.

253
00:11:14.730 --> 00:11:18.810
If female, you subtract 10.

254
00:11:18.810 --> 00:11:21.150
So men are at higher risk than women.

255
00:11:21.150 --> 00:11:23.580
That's why the sex of the patient

256
00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:25.500
was included in the stem of the question

257
00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:27.063
is because of this PSI.

258
00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:29.760
And then you move along.

259
00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:32.790
He doesn't have any of the rest of these risks,

260
00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:36.660
so he is stratified to Risk Class II.

261
00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:38.673
So that's the PSI and how it works.

262
00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:44.250
Class I or II, you could probably

263
00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:46.110
send them home on oral antibiotics.

264
00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:49.290
Class III, you may or you may not admit them to the hospital

265
00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:50.760
depending on other factors,

266
00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:53.410
and IV or V should all be hospitalized for treatment.

267
00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:55.770
Next question.

268
00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:57.930
So same case, you decide to treat

269
00:11:57.930 --> 00:11:59.670
your 55-year-old with pneumonia

270
00:11:59.670 --> 00:12:03.390
and history of diabetes and hypertension as an outpatient.

271
00:12:03.390 --> 00:12:04.770
The appropriate choice

272
00:12:04.770 --> 00:12:07.740
for outpatient treatment in this case

273
00:12:07.740 --> 00:12:09.450
is which one of the following?

274
00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:12.960
Is it A, amoxicillin?

275
00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:15.630
B, azithromycin?

276
00:12:15.630 --> 00:12:17.760
C, cefuroxime?

277
00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:20.043
Or D, levofloxacin?

278
00:12:23.370 --> 00:12:27.720
The key here is there's something about this patient

279
00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:30.120
that may be different from usual

280
00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:32.193
and that's what you have to identify.

281
00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:34.500
So again, it's asking you

282
00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:36.423
those two questions at once, right?

283
00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:40.230
Is this just a normal patient with no other risk factors

284
00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:43.470
and we need to stick with the first line agent,

285
00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:47.070
or is there an additional risk factor at play here

286
00:12:47.070 --> 00:12:50.913
that might kick us up into a further category?

287
00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:58.230
Good, the majority of you got the correct answer,

288
00:12:58.230 --> 00:12:59.370
which is levofloxacin.

289
00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:00.840
The reason is because he's diabetic.

290
00:13:00.840 --> 00:13:02.520
So let's get into these.

291
00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:04.710
So there are four treatment categories

292
00:13:04.710 --> 00:13:06.390
for community-acquired pneumonia.

293
00:13:06.390 --> 00:13:10.860
I should also say that healthcare-associated pneumonia,

294
00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:12.300
HCAP, that's gone now.

295
00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:14.277
How many remember that one, healthcare associated?

296
00:13:14.277 --> 00:13:16.320
No, no, no, it's out.

297
00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:19.020
It's all community-acquired pneumonia now

298
00:13:19.020 --> 00:13:20.100
with these new guidelines.

299
00:13:20.100 --> 00:13:21.870
So we have four treatment categories,

300
00:13:21.870 --> 00:13:23.633
this is pretty straightforward here.

301
00:13:24.660 --> 00:13:28.020
Category one is outpatient with he's healthy,

302
00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:31.593
no risks for drug resistant Strep or MRSA.

303
00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:34.410
No antibiotics in the last three months.

304
00:13:34.410 --> 00:13:36.480
Nothing else is going on.

305
00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:40.050
Number two, outpatient, but with comorbidities.

306
00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:44.130
In this case, our patient had what? Diabetes.

307
00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:45.780
So because he's diabetic,

308
00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:47.943
he's now in treatment category number two.

309
00:13:50.520 --> 00:13:52.140
Or if they've been on recent antibiotics

310
00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:52.980
in the past three months,

311
00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:55.410
including at the dentist or the urgent care.

312
00:13:55.410 --> 00:13:59.100
Keep that in mind that.

313
00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:01.560
That question in particular loves to show up on the boards

314
00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:03.153
about the recent antibiotics.

315
00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:08.280
A third treatment category is inpatient but not severe,

316
00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:10.230
so you need expanded coverage.

317
00:14:10.230 --> 00:14:14.190
And then your last treatment category is severe pneumonia

318
00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:15.720
as an inpatient or in the ICU

319
00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:16.560
and you're gonna throw everything,

320
00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:17.850
with the kitchen sink at those, right?

321
00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:18.780
So it's pretty straightforward.

322
00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:20.250
Let's take a look at them.

323
00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:22.260
So it has changed a bit.

324
00:14:22.260 --> 00:14:25.710
So treatment category one, outpatient, previously healthy,

325
00:14:25.710 --> 00:14:27.330
no risk for drug-resistant Strep.

326
00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:30.240
Amoxicillin is what we're back to.

327
00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:33.780
You can also use doxy if they're penicillin allergic.

328
00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:37.180
Macrolides again have fallen out of favor

329
00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:43.050
largely because of the resistance to Strep pneumo.

330
00:14:43.050 --> 00:14:46.140
So if your local resistance to Strep pneumo is low,

331
00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:49.020
you could still consider Zithromax.

332
00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:50.070
But for the purpose of the boards,

333
00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:51.620
I would stick with amoxicillin.

334
00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:54.840
Number two, outpatient with comorbidities

335
00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.700
or recent antibiotics.

336
00:14:56.700 --> 00:14:59.460
This was our 55-year-old with diabetes.

337
00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:02.130
You need to either do a beta-lactam plus a macrolide,

338
00:15:02.130 --> 00:15:05.460
so that would be Augmentin and Zithromax,

339
00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:08.850
or a respiratory quinolone.

340
00:15:08.850 --> 00:15:12.450
That's why the answer to that question was levofloxacin.

341
00:15:12.450 --> 00:15:14.460
The FDA statement on quinolones in 2016

342
00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:16.117
scared everybody to bits.

343
00:15:16.117 --> 00:15:17.880
"Oh my god, don't prescribe quinolones at all

344
00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:19.680
ever, ever, ever."

345
00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:20.673
Not quite.

346
00:15:22.847 --> 00:15:24.150
With serious bacterial infections,

347
00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:26.670
the benefits of quinolones outweigh the risk.

348
00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:29.880
So they get these prescriptions from the pharmacy

349
00:15:29.880 --> 00:15:32.430
and they have a list of warnings this long,

350
00:15:32.430 --> 00:15:34.713
and I future pace my patients.

351
00:15:35.670 --> 00:15:37.830
You're gonna get a scary list from CVS

352
00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:40.770
and you try not to pay too much attention

353
00:15:40.770 --> 00:15:44.043
because in your case, the benefit outweighs that risk.

354
00:15:45.810 --> 00:15:50.640
Okay, moving on to group number three, non-severe inpatient.

355
00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:52.320
You're gonna do the respiratory quinolone

356
00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:54.210
or the beta-lactam plus the macrolide,

357
00:15:54.210 --> 00:15:56.860
but in this case, it's probably gonna be intravenous.

358
00:15:57.990 --> 00:15:59.550
And then your severe patients,

359
00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:01.620
you're gonna do all of this plus more

360
00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:03.600
depending on, you know, what else you find

361
00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:06.393
with your antigen testing and cultures and so forth.

362
00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.540
So fairly straightforward.

363
00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:12.060
Now, this chart shows the differences

364
00:16:12.060 --> 00:16:16.740
between the 2007 guideline and the new 2019 guideline.

365
00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:19.410
So procalcitonin is out,

366
00:16:19.410 --> 00:16:21.843
corticosteroids are out unless they're septic.

367
00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:26.970
We no longer obtain a followup chest x-ray

368
00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:29.220
and the use of healthcare-associated pneumonia

369
00:16:29.220 --> 00:16:31.080
as a category is out.

370
00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:32.730
So those are the biggest changes.

371
00:16:34.710 --> 00:16:37.890
Okay, now let's move to another infection.

372
00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:39.840
So we've covered community-acquired pneumonia,

373
00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:42.180
I think pretty straightforward.

374
00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:45.030
Adult pertussis or whooping cough is next.

375
00:16:45.030 --> 00:16:47.670
This is, of course, due to Bordetella pertussis.

376
00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:50.370
I would memorize that bacteria name.

377
00:16:50.370 --> 00:16:54.990
They sometimes like to ask these questions as well.

378
00:16:54.990 --> 00:16:58.440
So do know that pertussis is due to Bordetella pertussis.

379
00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:00.480
It's in the name, pretty easy.

380
00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:01.740
So these patients just have

381
00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:05.010
cough, cough, cough, cough, cough that won't stop.

382
00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:07.320
They have paroxysms of cough

383
00:17:07.320 --> 00:17:11.190
that can actually fracture a rib or cause them to pass out.

384
00:17:11.190 --> 00:17:14.970
Way back in the day, we actually had a whoop

385
00:17:14.970 --> 00:17:17.353
where they would cough, cough, cough, cough, cough.

386
00:17:17.353 --> 00:17:19.500
(sucking in breath deeply)

387
00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:21.600
You know, they would suck in the air.

388
00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:23.160
That's the whoop from whooping cough.

389
00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:24.690
You don't really see that anymore,

390
00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:26.310
but you do see these persistent

391
00:17:26.310 --> 00:17:29.880
cough, cough, cough, cough, cough patients as adults.

392
00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.713
There's three stages to pertussis.

393
00:17:32.550 --> 00:17:34.830
Stage 1 is the catarrhal stage.

394
00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:37.380
You know, they're having upper respiratory type symptoms.

395
00:17:37.380 --> 00:17:40.020
A lot of mucus that's clear.

396
00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:42.963
If you can recognize it and treat it,

397
00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:47.280
you can shorten the disease course at this stage.

398
00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:48.900
So this is really interesting.

399
00:17:48.900 --> 00:17:51.270
In fact, they recommend that you do it.

400
00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:53.100
The problem is how?

401
00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:55.200
You know, a patient comes in with upper respiratory.

402
00:17:55.200 --> 00:17:58.143
I'm not always thinking pertussis.

403
00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:01.320
So it really is tricky.

404
00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:04.140
I guess you would, if on the boards,

405
00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:06.810
they would probably give you some extra information

406
00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:09.240
like recently exposed to pertussis

407
00:18:09.240 --> 00:18:11.233
and now presents with, you know,

408
00:18:11.233 --> 00:18:14.670
a respiratory symptom and cough,

409
00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:16.950
in which case you would treat.

410
00:18:16.950 --> 00:18:18.870
Stage 2 is the paroxysmal stage.

411
00:18:18.870 --> 00:18:20.340
This can go on for weeks

412
00:18:20.340 --> 00:18:23.190
where they have these uncontrolled paroxysms of cough.

413
00:18:23.190 --> 00:18:25.530
Treatment at this stage isn't gonna lessen their disease,

414
00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:27.870
but it might help prevent the spread.

415
00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:30.150
And then Stage 3 is the convalescent phase,

416
00:18:30.150 --> 00:18:31.440
which lasts a few weeks

417
00:18:31.440 --> 00:18:33.543
and they're still infectious at that time.

418
00:18:35.310 --> 00:18:38.280
You can diagnose this with nasal PCR testing more likely

419
00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:39.810
than to do a culture.

420
00:18:39.810 --> 00:18:41.820
And the treatment here is azithromycin

421
00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:45.360
'cause remember Zithromax and usually doxy

422
00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:47.730
will cover some of these atypical agents like this.

423
00:18:47.730 --> 00:18:50.643
So in this case, azithromycin is the drug of choice.

424
00:18:52.650 --> 00:18:55.470
Post-exposure prophylaxis would be recommended

425
00:18:55.470 --> 00:18:56.910
in household contacts.

426
00:18:56.910 --> 00:18:59.850
They did ask me that question last spring on the boards

427
00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:02.910
about a mother whose child had pertussis

428
00:19:02.910 --> 00:19:04.800
and what to do with her.

429
00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:07.023
And then the prevention is the TDAP vaccine.

430
00:19:08.970 --> 00:19:11.820
Viral lung infections, influenza is the most common.

431
00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:13.593
Of course, it's a winter spread.

432
00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:16.650
Very abrupt onset of symptoms.

433
00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:19.560
Patients with influenza will be like, "I was fine.

434
00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:23.430
And then boom, like it hit me like a Mack Truck,

435
00:19:23.430 --> 00:19:25.950
and now I've got the body aches, the cough, the fever.

436
00:19:25.950 --> 00:19:29.880
I went from, you know, it went from 0 to 100 like that."

437
00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:32.460
That's how fast influenza hits.

438
00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:34.953
Aerosolized spread like many viruses.

439
00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:38.850
The current recommendation by the CDC

440
00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:40.440
is not to wait on testing.

441
00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:42.510
If you have high clinical suspicion,

442
00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:44.310
you should go ahead and treat,

443
00:19:44.310 --> 00:19:48.903
especially if they are in a high risk group as listed.

444
00:19:50.970 --> 00:19:53.190
Tamiflu is still the preferred drug.

445
00:19:53.190 --> 00:19:55.080
You also have inhaled Relenza,

446
00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:57.380
unless you have a patient with asthma or COPD.

447
00:20:00.030 --> 00:20:03.183
Peramivir inpatient, and Xoflusa.

448
00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:07.900
Now, and don't forget, you can do chemoprophylaxis

449
00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:11.010
if a high-risk patient has been exposed

450
00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:13.653
or certainly you should in an institutional setting.

451
00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:19.380
What's interesting to me is that Tamiflu and Xoflusa

452
00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:20.760
work by different mechanisms,

453
00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:22.980
but I'm not aware of a clinical study

454
00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:25.350
that shows doing both at the same time.

455
00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:27.870
But I would be interested in that study.

456
00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:29.010
But for the purposes of the boards,

457
00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:30.810
Tamiflu is still the preferred drug.

458
00:20:31.651 --> 00:20:35.190
Okay, RSV, so much press and headlines

459
00:20:35.190 --> 00:20:36.843
RSV has gotten this year,

460
00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:39.960
very common also in the winter

461
00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:44.220
along with COVID and with influenza,

462
00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:46.860
so we have three circulating viruses now,

463
00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:48.900
not to mention adenovirus

464
00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:51.153
and all the other causes of the common cold.

465
00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:54.930
So most patients just have an upper respiratory type symptom

466
00:20:54.930 --> 00:20:55.950
for five days.

467
00:20:55.950 --> 00:20:59.370
Sicker patients are gonna get more pneumonia symptoms.

468
00:20:59.370 --> 00:21:01.860
And, of course, don't forget that your CHF patients,

469
00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:04.500
your asthmatics and COPDs are certainly gonna go into

470
00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:08.460
an exacerbation when they have an RSV infection.

471
00:21:08.460 --> 00:21:11.520
It's recommended that we should consider this in any adult

472
00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:13.650
with URI symptoms during the fall and winter

473
00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:15.870
and test them with PCR.

474
00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:18.420
The reason that it's nice to test

475
00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:21.840
'cause we have, you know, PCR testing now, I can do a swab

476
00:21:21.840 --> 00:21:26.840
and test for RSV, COVID, and influenza all at the same time.

477
00:21:27.030 --> 00:21:28.800
So the treatment changes,

478
00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:31.920
you know, depending on the result of that test.

479
00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:34.900
If it's RSV, that treatment is supportive

480
00:21:36.090 --> 00:21:37.980
provided they get over it within a week.

481
00:21:37.980 --> 00:21:41.640
You know, patients who you are sick longer than a week

482
00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:43.080
with their upper respiratory infection,

483
00:21:43.080 --> 00:21:44.230
we start thinking what?

484
00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:48.960
Rhinosinusitis, Dr. Holt talked about this earlier today.

485
00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:50.940
So that's that double whammy situation,

486
00:21:50.940 --> 00:21:54.330
you know, I had this upper respiratory infection,

487
00:21:54.330 --> 00:21:56.910
lasted about a week, I thought I was getting better,

488
00:21:56.910 --> 00:21:59.670
and then now it's back again with the,

489
00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:00.930
you know, the mucus production,

490
00:22:00.930 --> 00:22:01.800
blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

491
00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:03.810
That's the time that you would diagnose

492
00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:05.403
acute bacterial rhinosinusitis.

493
00:22:07.500 --> 00:22:10.080
Okay, now moving on to the difficult part,

494
00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:13.080
pneumococcal vaccinations, okay?

495
00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:14.490
David touched on this,

496
00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:17.550
but we're going to dive into it a little bit deeper.

497
00:22:17.550 --> 00:22:20.190
So we traditionally had two vaccines, right?

498
00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:23.430
We had the conjugate 13-valent vaccine

499
00:22:23.430 --> 00:22:25.950
that works via a T cell response.

500
00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:30.630
And then we had the polysaccharide 23-valent vaccine,

501
00:22:30.630 --> 00:22:33.750
which works via a B cell response, right?

502
00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:36.573
That's what we had, but it's changed.

503
00:22:37.650 --> 00:22:40.560
So next question. Same case.

504
00:22:40.560 --> 00:22:43.470
Our 55-year-old patient with diabetes and hypertension

505
00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:46.140
comes in for a routine health maintenance visit.

506
00:22:46.140 --> 00:22:49.290
They have no history of receiving a pneumococcal vaccine.

507
00:22:49.290 --> 00:22:53.430
When discussing vaccination for prevention of pneumonia,

508
00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:54.960
which one of the following options

509
00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:57.180
would be preferred in this case?

510
00:22:57.180 --> 00:23:02.180
A, PCV15 now and PPSV23 at age 65.

511
00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:06.870
So wait till he's 65 for one,

512
00:23:06.870 --> 00:23:08.280
give him the other now.

513
00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:11.013
B, PCV20 now.

514
00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:17.730
C, PPPSV23 at age 65 only.

515
00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:22.230
Or D, PPSV23 now and again at age 65.

516
00:23:22.230 --> 00:23:26.760
One of these is the preferred recommendation

517
00:23:26.760 --> 00:23:28.503
based on the newest guidelines.

518
00:23:33.990 --> 00:23:36.000
Okay, great, y'all are wonderful.

519
00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.960
So the correct answer is B, PCV20 now. Good.

520
00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:41.700
So we now have other options.

521
00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:44.760
In addition to the 13-valent conjugate, we have a 15-valent

522
00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:47.970
and a 20-valent conjugate vaccine

523
00:23:47.970 --> 00:23:52.380
in addition to the 23-valent polysaccharide vaccine.

524
00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:57.010
So we know that the PCV20 by itself

525
00:23:57.930 --> 00:24:02.040
or if you do the PCV15 in series a year later

526
00:24:02.040 --> 00:24:03.960
with the polysaccharide,

527
00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:06.780
very effective at reducing pneumococcal disease.

528
